                "section508Requirement": "36 CFR § 1194.22 - Document Accessibility",
                "impact": "high",
                "recommendation": "## ISSUE EXPLANATION\n\nThis PDF lacks proper tagging structure, which means screen readers and other assistive technologies cannot properly navigate or interpret the document content. This violates Section 508 § 1194.22(f) which requires documents to be organized so they are readable without requiring an associated style sheet, and WCAG 2.1 Success Criterion 1.3.1 (Info and Relationships) which mandates that information and structural relationships be programmatically determinable.\n\n## STEP-BY-STEP SOLUTION (Adobe Acrobat Pro)\n\n**Step 1:** Open the PDF in Adobe Acrobat Pro (not Reader)\n- Launch Adobe Acrobat Pro\n- Go to File > Open and select your \"valid.pdf\" file\n\n**Step 2:** Access the Accessibility Tools\n- Go to Tools > Accessibility in the top menu\n- Click \"Full Check\" to run a complete accessibility audit first\n\n**Step 3:** Add Tags to the Document\n- In the Accessibility panel, click \"Add Tags to Document\"\n- OR go to Tools > Accessibility > Add Tags to Document\n- Acrobat will automatically analyze and tag the document structure\n\n**Step 4:** Review and Refine Tag Structure\n- Open the Tags panel: View > Show/Hide > Navigation Panes > Tags (or press F6)\n- Examine the tag tree structure in the left panel\n- Right-click any incorrectly tagged elements and select \"Properties\" to modify tag types\n- Ensure headings are tagged as H1, H2, etc., and paragraphs as P tags\n\n**Step 5:** Set Reading Order (if needed)\n- Go to Tools > Accessibility > Reading Order\n- Use the Reading Order tool to adjust the logical flow of content\n- Click \"Show Order Panel\" to visualize reading sequence\n\n## VERIFICATION STEPS\n\n**Step 1:** Run Accessibility Check\n- Go to Tools > Accessibility > Full Check\n- Verify \"Tagged PDF\" shows as \"Passed\" in the results\n\n**Step 2:** Test Tag Structure\n- In the Tags panel, expand the tag tree\n- Confirm all content appears within appropriate tags\n- Use View > Read Out Loud > Read This Page Only to test screen reader functionality\n\n## ADDITIONAL NOTES\n\nSave the document after tagging (Ctrl+S) to preserve the accessibility structure. For documents with complex layouts, manual tag refinement may be necessary. Consider creating tagged PDFs from the source document (Word, InDesign) rather than retroactively tagging for better results.",
